# /etc/pam.d/erdtree — PAM stack for Erdtree login integration
#
# WHAT THIS IS
#   A conservative PAM service definition for the Erdtree product shell when
#   it is used as the login shell. Drop this file into /etc/pam.d/erdtree at
#   install time (Phase 11).
#
# WHAT THIS IS NOT
#   This file does NOT replace or modify sshd, login, or any other PAM service.
#   It defines the "erdtree" PAM service that pam_exec or a custom PAM module
#   can reference. Activating it (adding "session optional pam_exec.so ..." or
#   setting it as the login shell in /etc/passwd) is done by the installer,
#   not by this file.
#
# SAFETY PHILOSOPHY
#   - "required" for auth/account: a PAM failure means no login. Correct.
#   - "optional" for session extras: a failure in an Erdtree-specific session
#     module falls back gracefully (the user gets a bash session via the
#     dead-man fallback in shell.py) rather than locking them out.
#   - NO custom or third-party PAM modules are referenced here; only standard
#     modules that ship with Linux-PAM on RHEL-family systems.
#   - SELinux-aware: pam_selinux.so open/close is included; it is a no-op if
#     SELinux is permissive or disabled, and enforces context on enforcing hosts.
#
# LIVE ACTIVATION + /etc/passwd WIRING: DEFERRED — Phase 11 (install/).
#   Reason: requires a provisioned target host with root access and a real
#   /etc/passwd entry pointing to shell.py. Not testable on the build host
#   without root and without a full OS image. The PAM STACK ITSELF is authored
#   and statically reviewable here.
#
# I2: no "AI", "LLM", "model", "agent", or "agentic" in this file.
# I7: no "Rocky".

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# auth — verify the user's identity                                            #
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# Include the system-auth common stack (handles password, Kerberos, SSSD, etc.
# depending on what is configured on the host). Using "include" keeps us
# consistent with whatever authselect profile the admin has chosen.
auth       include      system-auth

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# account — enforce account validity (expiry, lockout, time restrictions)      #
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
account    required     pam_nologin.so
account    include      system-auth

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# password — change password (used when the session forces a password change)  #
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
password   include      system-auth

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# session — set up and tear down the user session                              #
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #

# SELinux context: open before anything else, close after everything else.
# These are no-ops if SELinux is disabled or permissive.
session    optional     pam_selinux.so open
session    required     pam_loginuid.so

# Standard session setup (limits, environment, keyring, etc.)
session    include      system-auth

# Log the session open/close to the system journal via utmp/wtmp.
session    optional     pam_lastlog.so showfailed
session    optional     pam_motd.so

# SELinux context close — must be last in session.
session    optional     pam_selinux.so close
